- 13.16 Closing — LLM as peer, not oracle

## 13.17 The grounded-vs-hallucinated principle

Every LLM-augmented verb obeys the same rule: try the mechanical layer first. Only speculate when the mechanical layer runs out. Always mark the return with `:grounded #t` or `:grounded #f` and, when not grounded, include a `:confidence` score.

This is what separates a useful peer verb from a dangerous one. A verb that always hallucinates is a liability. A verb that hallucinates only when it must, and marks the hallucination clearly, is a peer.

