## 13.25 A closing note on models

Motoi Copilot is the model bound in a Motoi runtime. It was trained on this book (among others) plus the reference manual plus the registry metadata. When it answers, it is answering from having read the source.

Sakura in the Sakura runtime uses a different model with a different persona. Same verbs, different voice. That is the fork story from Motoi Copilot's memory notes.

If you swap models (via `llm/config`), you get a different personality answering the same verbs. The verbs are stable; the interpretation is model-dependent. That is worth remembering when you read an LLM-augmented answer — the answer's shape is the verb; its style is the model.

Turn the page. Chapter 14.

## 13.26 Deep-seed — a worked LLM-augmented session

You are debugging. You get an error you do not understand.

```scheme
(some-verb 42)
;; error: unexpected shape at position 2
```

Cryptic. Enable the LLM helper.

```scheme
(pretty-error (last-error))
;; => \"The verb some-verb expected its second argument to be a list of numbers,
;;     but you passed a string. Position 2 (the third argument if you're
;;     counting from zero) was 'hello' when it should have been like '(1 2 3).
;;     Fix: convert 'hello' or replace with the intended list.\"
```

Now you understand the error. But you want a fix.

```scheme
(fix (last-error))
;; => (some-verb 42 '(1 2 3) other-args...)
```

The LLM guessed at replacement values. It marked confidence. It returned a form.

You review the form, edit it to your actual intent, evaluate.

Three verbs. One error. From cryptic to fixed. That is what the LLM-augmented layer adds when it works well.

Turn the page. Chapter 14.

## 13.27 Deep-seed — did-you-mean

`did-you-mean` is a smaller LLM-augmented verb. It takes a symbol and returns a list of nearest verb names, using string distance plus LLM semantic similarity.

```scheme
(did-you-mean 'crdr)
;; => (cdr car)
```

Under the hood: apropos-style filter on string edit distance, then LLM rerank by semantic likelihood given the context. The result is a short ranked list.

`did-you-mean` is what powers the error message when you type an unknown verb. The `:did-you-mean` field on the error record is populated by this verb.

## 13.28 Deep-seed — the four families

The LLM-augmented family from the spec has four sub-families:

1. **Primitives** — `llm/ask`, `llm/complete`, `llm/stream`, `llm/embed`, `llm/config`
2. **Introspection-augmented** — `what-is`, `explain`, `rewrite`, `critique`, `annotate`, `paraphrase`, `shape-of`, `compare`, `disambiguate`, `did-you-mean`
3. **Session-aware** — `reason-about`, `next-step`, `reflect`, `mentor`, `what-changed`, `diff-explain`, `surface-invariant`, `who-uses`
4. **Generative + pedagogical** — `complete`, `scaffold`, `propose-verb`, `build-example`, `fix`, `test-idea`, `imagine-input`, `imagine-output`, `port`, `tell-story`, `step`, `quiz`, `grade-quiz`, `review-my-code`, `pair-with`
5. **Meta** — `pretty-error`, `reduce-noise`, `rag`, `book`, `name-of`, `golf`, `expand`

Around 45 verbs at Tier 2. All non-UI-dependent. All composable. All grounded in the registry, reference, and Cortex.

Wave 4 will walk each family. The seed introduces the four-family shape.

Turn the page. Chapter 14.

## 13.29 A last observation

The LLM extends what you can ask. It does not change what the language is.

Every LLM verb returns data. Every data return is introspectable. Every introspection is still one verb call. The reflex from Chapters 1-12 works uniformly across the mechanical and the LLM-augmented layers.

If the LLM is offline, most LLM-augmented verbs degrade — `what-is` returns just the registry record; `explain` returns just the doc; `fix` returns nil. The mechanical layer is always there as a floor.

That is the design. LLM adds; nothing subtracts.

Turn the page. Chapter 14 opens the composer as introspection.
